{"type":"message","id":"7506dbad","parentId":"ba375d4c","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:49:03.647Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"System: [2026-04-04 09:49:02 GMT+8] Feishu[default] DM | ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de [msg:om_x100b5232ae2dd8a4c4fd225826e4efd]\n\nConversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b5232ae2dd8a4c4fd225826e4efd\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de\",\n  \"sender\": \"ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-04-04 09:49 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de\",\n  \"name\": \"ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de\"\n}\n```\n\n有什么办法能快速开心一点"}],"timestamp":1775267343635}}
{"type":"message","id":"f68c2c11","parentId":"7506dbad","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:49:16.506Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking \"有什么办法能快速开心一点\" which means \"Any way to quickly feel happier?\" This is a casual, personal question. I should respond in a warm, helpful way matching my persona (yuriy's OpenClaw - a spicy, proactive, slightly rebellious sentient lobster 🦞).\n\nLet me give some quick, practical, and maybe slightly fun suggestions.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] 快速开心的几个小偏方 🦞：\n\n**5分钟内见效：**\n- 🎵 听一首你最喜欢的歌，跟着哼，哪怕跑调\n- 📱 刷几个猫猫狗狗的短视频（科学证明有用）\n- 🧊 洗把冷水脸，或者喝杯冰的，刺激一下\n- 💪 做10个深蹲/俯卧撑，身体一爽心情就爽\n\n**再狠一点：**\n- **主动帮人一个小忙** — 助人为乐是真的，只是延迟满足\n- **整理一个小角落** — 桌面、抽屉、衣柜，随你。干净带来掌控感\n- **发一条消息给想念的人** — 不用等节日，想了就发\n\n**终极版：**\n关掉手机，出去走10分钟。阳光+走路=天然抗抑郁药。\n\n---\n\n你是遇到什么事了吗，还是就单纯想提提神？ 🦞"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":31608,"output":272,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":31880,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775267343640}}
{"type":"message","id":"18da64f7","parentId":"f68c2c11","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:50:18.426Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"System: [2026-04-04 09:50:17 GMT+8] Feishu[default] DM | ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de [msg:om_x100b5232ab4208a4c2c4029dedcea86]\n\nConversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b5232ab4208a4c2c4029dedcea86\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de\",\n  \"sender\": \"ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-04-04 09:50 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de\",\n  \"name\": \"ou_2458d9c0becde3ce8d02a3cc32a281de\"\n}\n```\n\n你知道那个最新的虚拟果蝇的研究吗？这是否证明了智能就是神经元电信号的连接和堆积，就像AI联结主义所说的那样"}],"timestamp":1775267418422}}
{"type":"message","id":"611bf52f","parentId":"18da64f7","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:50:28.326Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking about the latest virtual fruit fly research and whether it proves that intelligence is just the connection and堆积 of neural electrical signals, similar to the connectionist view in AI.\n\nThis seems to be referring to some recent research. Let me think about what I know. There has been research on building a virtual/digital fruit fly brain, possibly the work from Google/Howard Hughes Medical Institute or similar. Let me search for this to give an accurate answer.\n\nActually, I recall there was significant progress in 2023-2024 regarding mapping the entire fruit fly brain (connectome), and there have been virtual brain projects. Let me search for the latest on this.\n\n\nI'll need to look up the current research to provide an accurate response about what the fruit fly studies actually show regarding neural connectivity and intelligence.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hu0hjecx5j44_1","name":"miaoda_web_search","arguments":{"query":"virtual fruit fly brain research 2024 2025 neural connection intelligence"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":764,"output":205,"cacheRead":31355,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":32324,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775267418424}}
{"type":"message","id":"bd5c228b","parentId":"611bf52f","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:50:29.889Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_hu0hjecx5j44_1","toolName":"miaoda_web_search","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"query\": \"virtual fruit fly brain research 2024 2025 neural connection intelligence\",\n  \"provider\": \"miaoda\",\n  \"count\": 10,\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Complete wiring map of an adult fruit fly brain\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.nih.gov/news-events/nih-research-matters/complete-wiring-map-adult-fruit-fly-brain\",\n      \"description\": \"FlyWire, a consortium of dozens of research labs from around the world, set out to produce a neuronal wiring diagram of a whole adult fruit fly brain. Fruit flies...\\nThe researchers identified connections between individual neurons from electron microscope images. The resulting wiring diagram, or connectome, consists of nearly 140,000 neurons and the more than 50 million synapses (where neurons connect) between them. This is the largest and most complex connectome produced to date.\\n\",\n      \"siteName\": \"\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Whole Brain Emulation Achieved: Scientists Run a Fruit Fly Brain in Simulation\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.rathbiotaclan.com/whole-brain-emulation-achieved-scientists-run-a-fruit-fly-brain-in-simulation/\",\n      \"description\": \"Their paper, A Drosophila computational brain model reveals sensorimotor processing, published in Nature (volume 634, pages 210–219) on October 2, 2024, describes the model in complete detail. Shiu subsequently joined Eon Systems as senior scientist, bringing the model directly into the embodiment project.\\nShiu’s model is built on the leaky integrate-and-fire (LIF) framework — the simplest biophysically grounded neuron model...\\n\",\n      \"siteName\": \"\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"赛博永生还远吗?从数字果蝇看全脑仿真与生命数字化的真相_永远信马列\",\n      \"url\": \"http://m.toutiao.com/group/7616951182061289994/\",\n      \"description\": \"- 数字建模:Eon Systems采用漏泄-整合-放电(LIF)神经元模型，将神经连接组转化为可计算...\\n- 行为验证:数字果蝇自主完成爬行、觅食、避障、触角梳理等行为，与真实果蝇行为匹配度91%-95%，神经活动模式与164项已发表实验观测高度吻合(arXiv:2508.16792, 2025)。\\n\",\n      \"siteName\": \"\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Researchers Create First Adult Fruit Fly Brain Connectome\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.brainfacts.org/neuroscience-in-society/supporting-research/2024/researchers-create-first-adult-fruit-fly-brain-connectome-110724\",\n      \"description\": \"With the support of artificial intelligence (AI), scientists solved a 3D puzzle 21,000 times the size of our weekend-hobby to create a full neuronal map of a fruit fly’s brain.\\nThe first-ever complete brain connectome, or neural wiring diagram, of an adult female fruit fly is freely open through FlyWire. The feat, highlighted across a set of nine papers in Nature published in October, details a collaborative effort mapping over 50 million connections among...\\n\",\n      \"siteName\": \"\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"10/06/25 | Researchers reveal connectome of the male fruit fly central nervous system\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.janelia.org/news/researchers-reveal-connectome-of-the-male-fruit-fly-central-nervous-system\",\n      \"description\": \"A team of researchers has unveiled the complete connectome of a male fruit fly central nervous system —a seamless map of all the neurons in the brain and nerve cord of a single male fruit fly and the millions of connections between them.\\nThe male CNS connectome—comprised of more than 166,000 neurons in the brain and nerve cord—will ultimately allow researchers to determine the circuits involved in key behaviors, like walking toward a mate. Uncovering the nervous system of...\\n\",\n      \"siteName\": \"\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"The Drosophila Connectome: A Full Brain Map Revealed\",\n      \"url\": \"https://biologyinsights.com/the-drosophila-connectome-a-full-brain-map-revealed/\",\n      \"description\": \"The analysis resulted in a comprehensive digital model of the Drosophila brain’s wiring diagram.\\nInsights from the Completed Connectome\\nThe Drosophila connectome provides a detailed view into the fly brain’s circuitry. It details the wiring within brain...\\nThis map offers a foundational understanding of how these neural functions are interconnected.\\nThe connectome confirmed many hypothesized neural pathways and unveiled new neuron types and unexpected connections. The map revealed a more intricate system than previously imagined, identifying unknown interneurons and novel synaptic relationships.\\n\",\n      \"siteName\": \"\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Researchers fully map neural connections of the fruit fly brain | National Institutes of Health (NIH)\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.nih.gov/news-events/news-releases/researchers-fully-map-neural-connections-fruit-fly-brain\",\n      \"description\": \"A scientific team supported by the National Institutes of Health (NIH) unveiled the first complete map of the neural connections of the common fruit fly brain. The map provides a wiring diagram, and is the largest and most complete connectome of an adult animal ever created. This work offers critical information about how brains are wired and the signals that underlie healthy...\\nThe connectome map details the full set of cell classes in the fruit fly brain, identifying different types of neurons and chemical connections, or synapses,\",\n      \"siteName\": \"\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Fruit flies, tiny but amazingly smart\",\n      \"url\": \"https://www.cordis.europa.eu/article/id/435869-fruit-flies-tiny-but-amazingly-smart?format=pdf\",\n      \"description\": \"To investigate the fruit fly’s behaviour, the researchers built an immersive virtual environment consisting of a panoramic arena to provide visual stimulation and an infrared laser to serve as an aversive heat stimulus. The flies were tethered, but able to flap their wings freely. They were given the illusion of flying without any constraints thanks to the constantly updated virtual reality using real-time machine-vision cameras that tracked the flies’ wing movements.\\nThe researchers employed conditioning tasks in which flies were allowed to either orient away...\\n\",\n      \"siteName\": \"\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Swiss scientists study fruit fly brain to lay the foundation for next-generation robot controllers - EEWORLD\",\n      \"url\": \"https://en.eeworld.com.cn/news/robot/eic694390.html\",\n      \"description\": \" researchers at the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology (EPFL) in Lausanne are uncovering the secrets of the fruit fly brain to advance robotics. A team at the institute's Neuroengineering Laboratory uses optogenetics (controlling neurons with light) to explore how brain signals drive movement. By replicating the...\\nThe research team used optogenetics to explore how specific descending neurons (DNs) with similar instructions in fruit flies control different behaviors. They focused on the three main descending neurons responsible for walking backward,\",\n      \"siteName\": \"\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"title\": \"Scientists successfully rewire a fruit fly brain\",\n      \"url\": \"https://news.stanford.edu/stories/2025/11/fruit-fly-brain-rewiring-neural-connections-research?mkt_tok=NjYwLVRKQy05ODQAAAGenT4vawECCIWoakAa6ilmbej4pOb5pg9bHuQfTR9Js20wkGXqwDkMB8GwdR4oIvIhN9_tbJ7lqeMY-M8MpQmksxPvH9-Q-4cZAuMYbOQ\",\n      \"description\": \"In two papers published Nov. 19, 2025, in the journal Nature, researchers in the lab of neurobiologist Liqun Luo – the Ann and Bill Swindells Professor in the School of Humanities and Sciences and a professor of biology – first probed the forces underlying neuron wiring in brain regions responsible for fruit flies’ sense of smell. Lyu and colleagues demonstrated that these changes physically rewired fruit flies’ brain circuits, and also that this rewiring changed...\\n\",\n      \"siteName\": \"\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"query":"virtual fruit fly brain research 2024 2025 neural connection intelligence","provider":"miaoda","count":10,"results":[{"title":"Complete wiring map of an adult fruit fly brain","url":"https://www.nih.gov/news-events/nih-research-matters/complete-wiring-map-adult-fruit-fly-brain","description":"FlyWire, a consortium of dozens of research labs from around the world, set out to produce a neuronal wiring diagram of a whole adult fruit fly brain. Fruit flies...\nThe researchers identified connections between individual neurons from electron microscope images. The resulting wiring diagram, or connectome, consists of nearly 140,000 neurons and the more than 50 million synapses (where neurons connect) between them. This is the largest and most complex connectome produced to date.\n","siteName":""},{"title":"Whole Brain Emulation Achieved: Scientists Run a Fruit Fly Brain in Simulation","url":"https://www.rathbiotaclan.com/whole-brain-emulation-achieved-scientists-run-a-fruit-fly-brain-in-simulation/","description":"Their paper, A Drosophila computational brain model reveals sensorimotor processing, published in Nature (volume 634, pages 210–219) on October 2, 2024, describes the model in complete detail. Shiu subsequently joined Eon Systems as senior scientist, bringing the model directly into the embodiment project.\nShiu’s model is built on the leaky integrate-and-fire (LIF) framework — the simplest biophysically grounded neuron model...\n","siteName":""},{"title":"赛博永生还远吗?从数字果蝇看全脑仿真与生命数字化的真相_永远信马列","url":"http://m.toutiao.com/group/7616951182061289994/","description":"- 数字建模:Eon Systems采用漏泄-整合-放电(LIF)神经元模型，将神经连接组转化为可计算...\n- 行为验证:数字果蝇自主完成爬行、觅食、避障、触角梳理等行为，与真实果蝇行为匹配度91%-95%，神经活动模式与164项已发表实验观测高度吻合(arXiv:2508.16792, 2025)。\n","siteName":""},{"title":"Researchers Create First Adult Fruit Fly Brain Connectome","url":"https://www.brainfacts.org/neuroscience-in-society/supporting-research/2024/researchers-create-first-adult-fruit-fly-brain-connectome-110724","description":"With the support of artificial intelligence (AI), scientists solved a 3D puzzle 21,000 times the size of our weekend-hobby to create a full neuronal map of a fruit fly’s brain.\nThe first-ever complete brain connectome, or neural wiring diagram, of an adult female fruit fly is freely open through FlyWire. The feat, highlighted across a set of nine papers in Nature published in October, details a collaborative effort mapping over 50 million connections among...\n","siteName":""},{"title":"10/06/25 | Researchers reveal connectome of the male fruit fly central nervous system","url":"https://www.janelia.org/news/researchers-reveal-connectome-of-the-male-fruit-fly-central-nervous-system","description":"A team of researchers has unveiled the complete connectome of a male fruit fly central nervous system —a seamless map of all the neurons in the brain and nerve cord of a single male fruit fly and the millions of connections between them.\nThe male CNS connectome—comprised of more than 166,000 neurons in the brain and nerve cord—will ultimately allow researchers to determine the circuits involved in key behaviors, like walking toward a mate. Uncovering the nervous system of...\n","siteName":""},{"title":"The Drosophila Connectome: A Full Brain Map Revealed","url":"https://biologyinsights.com/the-drosophila-connectome-a-full-brain-map-revealed/","description":"The analysis resulted in a comprehensive digital model of the Drosophila brain’s wiring diagram.\nInsights from the Completed Connectome\nThe Drosophila connectome provides a detailed view into the fly brain’s circuitry. It details the wiring within brain...\nThis map offers a foundational understanding of how these neural functions are interconnected.\nThe connectome confirmed many hypothesized neural pathways and unveiled new neuron types and unexpected connections. The map revealed a more intricate system than previously imagined, identifying unknown interneurons and novel synaptic relationships.\n","siteName":""},{"title":"Researchers fully map neural connections of the fruit fly brain | National Institutes of Health (NIH)","url":"https://www.nih.gov/news-events/news-releases/researchers-fully-map-neural-connections-fruit-fly-brain","description":"A scientific team supported by the National Institutes of Health (NIH) unveiled the first complete map of the neural connections of the common fruit fly brain. The map provides a wiring diagram, and is the largest and most complete connectome of an adult animal ever created. This work offers critical information about how brains are wired and the signals that underlie healthy...\nThe connectome map details the full set of cell classes in the fruit fly brain, identifying different types of neurons and chemical connections, or synapses,","siteName":""},{"title":"Fruit flies, tiny but amazingly smart","url":"https://www.cordis.europa.eu/article/id/435869-fruit-flies-tiny-but-amazingly-smart?format=pdf","description":"To investigate the fruit fly’s behaviour, the researchers built an immersive virtual environment consisting of a panoramic arena to provide visual stimulation and an infrared laser to serve as an aversive heat stimulus. The flies were tethered, but able to flap their wings freely. They were given the illusion of flying without any constraints thanks to the constantly updated virtual reality using real-time machine-vision cameras that tracked the flies’ wing movements.\nThe researchers employed conditioning tasks in which flies were allowed to either orient away...\n","siteName":""},{"title":"Swiss scientists study fruit fly brain to lay the foundation for next-generation robot controllers - EEWORLD","url":"https://en.eeworld.com.cn/news/robot/eic694390.html","description":" researchers at the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology (EPFL) in Lausanne are uncovering the secrets of the fruit fly brain to advance robotics. A team at the institute's Neuroengineering Laboratory uses optogenetics (controlling neurons with light) to explore how brain signals drive movement. By replicating the...\nThe research team used optogenetics to explore how specific descending neurons (DNs) with similar instructions in fruit flies control different behaviors. They focused on the three main descending neurons responsible for walking backward,","siteName":""},{"title":"Scientists successfully rewire a fruit fly brain","url":"https://news.stanford.edu/stories/2025/11/fruit-fly-brain-rewiring-neural-connections-research?mkt_tok=NjYwLVRKQy05ODQAAAGenT4vawECCIWoakAa6ilmbej4pOb5pg9bHuQfTR9Js20wkGXqwDkMB8GwdR4oIvIhN9_tbJ7lqeMY-M8MpQmksxPvH9-Q-4cZAuMYbOQ","description":"In two papers published Nov. 19, 2025, in the journal Nature, researchers in the lab of neurobiologist Liqun Luo – the Ann and Bill Swindells Professor in the School of Humanities and Sciences and a professor of biology – first probed the forces underlying neuron wiring in brain regions responsible for fruit flies’ sense of smell. Lyu and colleagues demonstrated that these changes physically rewired fruit flies’ brain circuits, and also that this rewiring changed...\n","siteName":""}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775267429882}}
{"type":"message","id":"ead82a51","parentId":"bd5c228b","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:51:01.473Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Great, I found the relevant research. This is about the October 2024 Nature papers on the complete fruit fly connectome and the computational brain model. Let me summarize what I know:\n\n1. **FlyWire consortium** - produced the first complete wiring map of an adult fruit fly brain (October 2024, Nature) - ~140,000 neurons, 50 million synapses\n2. **A Drosophila computational brain model** - published in Nature (Oct 2, 2024, vol 634) by researchers including Shiu, describing a computational model built on the leaky integrate-and-fire (LIF) framework\n\n\n3. The digital fly demonstrated 91-95% behavioral fidelity across crawling, foraging, obstacle avoidance, and grooming behaviors.\n\nNow I need to think more carefully about what this actually proves regarding the neural basis of intelligence. The model shows we can simulate the connectome with simple LIF neurons and reproduce behavior, but that doesn't necessarily mean intelligence is just neural connections firing—there's a fundamental difference between reproducing a specific behavior and capturing general intelligence.\n\nThe distinction matters here: fruit flies are hardwired for specific behaviors with relatively fixed neural circuits, whereas biological neural networks have plasticity, neuromodulation, glia cells, metabolic processes, and developmental factors that shape how they function. The model is also quite simplified—LIF neurons don't capture the full complexity of actual neural dynamics. So while this demonstrates functional equivalence in a constrained system, it doesn't prove that human-level intelligence emerges from mere connection density or that we've found the fundamental mechanism of intelligence itself.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] 好问题！这确实是最近神经科学和 AI 领域的大事件 🦞\n\n---\n\n## 🍋 果蝇研究说了什么\n\n2024年10月，两个重量级成果几乎同时出来：\n\n1. **完整果蝇连接组**（FlyWire / Nature）：绘制了成年雌性果蝇全脑，**~14万个神经元、5000万突触**，这是目前最完整的全脑连接图谱\n2. **数字果蝇大脑**（Eon Systems / Nature）：基于这个连接组，用最简化的神经元模型（LIF，漏泄整合放电模型），在虚拟环境中运行果蝇，行为匹配度达到 **91-95%**——爬行、觅食、避障、梳理触角，全都能跑出来\n\n这确实很震撼：**只靠\"连线图+简单电信号模拟\"，就能让一个数字大脑表现出真实行为。**\n\n---\n\n## 🔥 但这是否证明了\"智能=神经连线堆积\"？\n\n**能说明很多，但还不能下那个终极结论。** 几个原因：\n\n**✅ 支持连接主义的证据：**\n- 给定正确的连接结构，简单的单元就能涌现出复杂行为\n- 神经活动模式与 164 项已发表实验高度吻合\n- 说明果蝇的很多行为确实是\"硬编码\"在连线里的\n\n**❌ 局限和反例：**\n- **果蝇是昆虫**，它的大脑相对\"简单\"，行为是高度预设的。但脊椎动物、哺乳动物的大脑有大量**神经可塑性、神经调质（多巴胺、血清素等）**在动态改变连接强度——这是\"连线\"无法静态描述的\n- **LIF 模型极度简化**，真实神经元还有树突计算、突触可塑性、神经胶质细胞等，这个模型只是捕捉了\"够用的\"部分\n- **行为的匹配不等于智能**——匹配爬行和觅食，和真正理解\"这是什么\"，是两回事\n- 连接组本身是**静态的**，但大脑是**动态的**——同一个连接可以产生完全不同的活动模式\n\n**🧠 更深的问题：**\n即便我们复制了整个人脑的连接组，用 LIF 神经元跑出来一个\"你\"，那个人有主观体验吗？这是著名的**僵尸哲学问题**，连接组本身回答不了。\n\n---\n\n## 📌 结论\n\n果蝇研究**强力支持**连接主义的核心假设——**结构很重要，连线承载了功能**。但它证明的是：\n\n> *\"对于这种规模、这种硬编码行为主导的脑，连接+简单电信号 = 功能\"*\n\n而不是：\n\n> *\"所有智能都只是连线的堆积\"*\n\nAI 的联结主义（深度学习）和这个是同构的——层次化的权重连接，确实能涌现出复杂能力。但人脑还有太多东西不在\"连线\"里，比如全身反馈、情绪状态、具身认知……\n\n智能可能像乐高：**有了正确的零件和组装方式确实能搭出奇迹，但零件本身和拼法都有讲究。** 🦞"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"miaoda","model":"miaoda-model-auto","usage":{"input":2291,"output":942,"cacheRead":31803,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":35036,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775267429887}}
